Supervised Learning Project MSCS 5622

Project by Sean Norman | April 2025

Executive Summary

Analyze the relationship between Consumer Price Index (CPI) and revolving consumer credit volume using monthly data from 2019 through early 2025 for exploratory data analysis (EDA) and model training, and test predictive models on subsequent monthly data (JanuaryMarch 2025). This analysis would be useful in better understanding when revolving consumer credit volume is expected to bloom as a result of the CPI trends. If this could be determined it may inform personal actions that could be taken to prevent investment risk or capitalize on opportunities.

Data Source Reference:

  • U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. (2025). Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U): U.S. city average, All series [CUUR0000+]. Retrieved from https://data.bls.gov/dataViewer/view/timeseries/CUUR0000SA0
  • Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis. (2025). Consumer Credit Outstanding (Levels), Revolving [REVOLNS]. Retrieved from https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/REVOLNS

Load and clean the CPI Data

The CPI Data contains extra rows as it is an XLSX file in addition to additional columns that refer to different half durations of a given annum. To best utilize the data we will need to transpose the data eventually so that the date can be an index and the features are the respective columns.

Since we pulled all series available for CPI data we should drop these as they won't be relevant or able to be impute missing values given the quantity of gaps in the data. This should be okay as there are many feautres to still use and some top level categorical features exist in this set too.

We are going to create a filtered set of features based on the major expenditure categories (mec) defined by BLS. For reference, see https://www.bls.gov/cpi/additional-resources/cpi-item-aggregation.htm

the major_expenditure_categories will have both a Name and a 3-digit code. The 3-digit code follows the base_code prefix for our series features of 'CUUR0000' to create the major series names.

For this analysis we will only focus on the major categories vs analyzing the hundreds of sub categories.

In[223]:
# Create a list of major expenditure categories that comprise of the name of the major expenditure category and the corresponding code
major_expenditure_categories = [
    ('Food_and_Beverages', 'SAF'),
    ('Housing', 'SAH'),
    ('Apparel', 'SAA'),
    ('Transportation', 'SAT'),
    ('Medical_Care', 'SAM'),
    ('Recreation', 'SAR'),
    ('Education_and_Communication', 'SAE'),

]

After performing this initial EDA we can see there is strong multicollinearity of the data which also seems representative from when we calculated the correlation matrix.

According to some research we should calculate the variance inflation factor (VIF) for each predictor to determine the multicollinearity. We will do this next.

**note: below is the VIF analysis and in learning more about collinearity I increased the samples to be from 2019 forward vs just 2023 forward. In doing so I noticed that Housing, Medical Care, and Education and Communication have the best performing P values.

ML Modeling

In the below section we will explore trying Random Forest and Gradient Boosting models to determine impact of CPI categories on the overall REVOLNS.

Random Forest will help address potential challenges with the multicollinearity. As I read up on Random Forest I was learning that we need to handle time-series data slightly differently to handle the autocorrelation. This will be done by establishing new lagging features for each of our major category features of CPI.

Creating the lagging features for:

  • 1 period lag
  • 2 period lag
  • 3 period lag
In[233]:
# Create three new features for each major expenditure category based on one month, two months and three months lagged values
# Create new dataframe to hold the lagged features and the previous df cpi_revolns_major
ml_df = cpi_revolns_major.copy()

# Create lagged features for each major expenditure category

# Create 1-month lagged features
for category, code in major_expenditure_categories:
    ml_df[f'{category}_1m'] = ml_df[category].shift(1)

# Create 2-month lagged features
for category, code in major_expenditure_categories:
    ml_df[f'{category}_2m'] = ml_df[category].shift(2)

# Create 3-month lagged features
for category, code in major_expenditure_categories:
    ml_df[f'{category}_3m'] = ml_df[category].shift(3)

# Drop the first three rows with NaN values
ml_df = ml_df.dropna()

# Display the first few rows of the modified DataFrame with a category and a lagged feature
display(ml_df[['Date', 'Housing', 'Housing_1m', 'Housing_2m', 'Housing_3m']].head())

In[237]:
# Set up the RF model for hyperparameter tuning
rf_model_tune = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)
# Define the parameter grid for hyperparameter tuning

param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200, 300],
    'max_depth': [5, 10, 20, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 5, 10],
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', None, 0.33, 0.5],
    'max_leaf_nodes': [None, 10, 20, 50],
    'bootstrap': [True, False],
    'ccp_alpha': [0.0, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1]
}


tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5)

random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    rf_model_tune,
    param_distributions=param_dist,
    n_iter=50,  # Number of parameter combinations to try
    cv=tscv,
    scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
    n_jobs=-1,
    random_state=42
)

# Fit the model
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

rf_tune_rmse = np.sqrt(-random_search.best_score_)

param_dist_xgb = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 150, 200],
    'max_depth': [3, 4, 5, 6 ],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2],
    'subsample': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'colsample_bytree': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'gamma': [0, 0.1, 0.2],
    'reg_alpha': [0, 0.01, 0.1, 0.5],
    'reg_lambda': [0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 5.0]
}

# Time-series cross-validation

# Randomized search
random_search_xgb = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb_model_tune,
    param_distributions=param_dist_xgb,
    n_iter=50,  # Number of parameter combinations to try

    scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
    n_jobs=-1,
    random_state=42,

)

Recap and summary of approach

GOAL: This notebook focused on understanding how the Consumer Price Index across Major Expenditure Categories contributes to the Revolving Consumer Credit amount

To seek this goal we peformed:

  1. Data Collection, Preparation, and Cleaning
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  3. Initial Modeling and Multicollinearity Assessment
  4. Advanced Machine Learning (ML) Model Development

Data Collection and Preparation

  • Data Acquisition: Obtained Consumer Price Index (CPI) data from the US Bureau of Labor Statistics and revolving credit (REVOLNS) data from FRED.
  • Data Cleaning: Handled formatting issues, removed irrelevant rows, standardized date formats, and aligned timeframes between datasets.
  • Feature Selection: Focused on major expenditure categories defined by BLS rather than analyzing hundreds of sub-categories.
  • Missing Data Management: Identified and dropped columns with missing values after visualizing the extent of missingness.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

  • Distribution Analysis: Examined distributions of each major expenditure category and checked for outliers.
  • Correlation Analysis: Created correlation matrices to understand relationships between CPI categories and revolving credit.
  • Visual Exploration: Generated scatter plots, pair plots, and time series visualizations to identify patterns and relationships.
  • Seasonality Assessment: Evaluated potential seasonality in both CPI categories and revolving credit over time.

Initial Modeling Approach

  • Linear Regression: Started with a simple multiple linear regression model using all major CPI categories.
  • Multicollinearity Assessment: Calculated Variance Inflation Factors (VIFs) to quantify the extreme multicollinearity.
  • Model Refinement: Iteratively simplified the model by reducing features, ultimately focusing on Housing and Apparel as predictors.

Advanced Machine Learning Approach

  • Feature Engineering:

Created temporal context by generating 1-month, 2-month, and 3-month lagged features for each CPI category. Expanded the dataset timeframe to increase observations (starting from 2019 instead of 2023).

  • Time Series Handling:

Implemented proper time-based train-test splitting to maintain temporal integrity. Used TimeSeriesSplit for cross-validation during hyperparameter tuning.

  • Model Development:

    • Random Forest Regression:

      • Implemented baseline model with default parameters
      • Conducted extensive hyperparameter tuning using RandomizedSearchCV
      • Analyzed feature importance rankings

    • XGBoost Regression:

      • Implemented baseline model
      • Performed hyperparameter optimization across multiple parameters
      • Extracted and analyzed feature importance patterns

  • Model Evaluation:

    • Calculated multiple performance metrics: RMSE, R, and relative RMSE
    • Visualized actual vs. predicted values
    • Analyzed residuals to assess model fit
    • Compared performance across different algorithms and configurations

Findings and conclusion

Learnings and takeaways

  1. Strong Housing-Credit Relationship: Housing has the highest correlation (0.922) with revolving credit (REVOLNS), suggesting housing costs are a primary driver of credit card debt. This makes intuitive sense as housing represents the largest expense category for most households.

  2. Significant Multicollinearity: Extreme multicollinearity exists between CPI categories (especially Housing and Other Goods/Services at 0.999 correlation), which complicated model building and interpretation.

  3. XGBoost Outperformed Other Models:

  • XGBoost models (R = 0.22) substantially outperformed Random Forest models (negative R values)
  • Hyperparameter tuning provided modest improvements over base models
  • Relative RMSE for XGBoost (~1.7%) indicates good prediction accuracy despite modest R values
  • Limited Explanatory Power: Even the best models explain only about 20-22% of the variance in revolving credit, suggesting that while CPI categories influence credit card debt, other significant factors are at play.

  1. Temporal Features Matter: The creation of lagged features (1-month, 2-month, 3-month) improved model performance, with several lagged variables appearing as important predictors in the final models.

  2. Feature Importance Insights: The XGBoost model's feature importance analysis revealed that Housing and its lagged versions were consistently the most important predictors, reinforcing the correlation findings.

  3. Surprisingly Low Variability: Many CPI categories showed limited variability over time, making their predictive power less substantial than initially expected.

  4. Category Differentiation: Apparel showed lower correlation with other CPI categories, suggesting it captures somewhat different economic dynamics than other categories.

  5. Relative vs. Absolute Prediction Accuracy: While absolute R values were modest, the low relative RMSE (~1.7%) suggests the models have practical predictive utility despite not capturing all factors affecting revolving credit.

  6. Linear Models Struggled: The initial linear regression models were heavily impacted by multicollinearity, requiring significant simplification to achieve stable results.

Suggested improvements

  1. Explore additional datasets to enrich CPI with other factors for a complete view of what impacts the Consumer Revolving Credit

  2. Address Multicollinearity: there might be ways to expand the dataset or use different analysis to manage the multicollinearity that was identified during the EDA and initial analysis

  3. Lagging features for 1, 2, and 3 months respectively were added to the dataset and that helped with the ML model performance as these features were impactful in determining the best results. With a larger observational dataset we could begin looking at 6 and 12 month lagging impact as well. This would be a good next step if not enriching the CPI data with any further data sources.

  4. Explore additional derivative measures to identify movement period/period that could support insights around rate of change of the given CPI categories.

Considerations for the future

  1. Prioritize additional data such as consumer credit rates, unemployment rate, consumer confidence, retail sales, and disposible income.

  2. Generate different models that handle time-series data more effectively than those used in this analysis. Light research online suggests that there are more appropriate time-series modeling techniques to account for unobserved factors.

  3. Consider other sub-categories within the major expenditure categories of the CPI data
